<chapter xml:id="ch_magnetism" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Magnetism</title>
	<introduction>
    <p> In this chapter you will learn how to model magnetism.</p>
	
	<p><alert>Learning Outcomes</alert></p>
  
	<p>
		After successful completion of this chapter, you will be able to:
		<ol>
			<li>Determine the magnetic field at a given location due to a collection of line currents.</li>
<li>Determine the magnetic force on a charged object with a given speed due to a magnetic field.</li>
<li>Use forces and Newton’s 2nd Law to describe the motion of charges subject to magnetic forces.</li>
<li>Distinguish between the magnetic force and the magnetic field.</li>
<li>Apply Ampere’s Law to arbitrary loops.</li>
<li>Use Ampere's Law to solve for the magnetic field in symmetric situations.</li>
<li>Determine the magnetic potential energy of a magnetic dipole in a magnetic field.</li>
<li>Determine the torque on a magnetic dipole due to a magnetic field.</li>
<li>Use Faraday's Law to find the induced voltage due to changing magnetic fields.</li>
<li>Describe the behavior of simple LC and LR circuits qualitatively and quantitatively.</li>

		</ol>
	</p>

